WEBVTT

1
00:00.300 --> 00:03.960
- Welcome back to Understanding Quantum Information and Computation.

2
00:03.960 --> 00:09.900
My name is John Watrous and I'm the Technical Director for
Education at IBM Quantum.

3
00:09.900 --> 00:19.170
This is the seventh lesson of the series and in this lesson we'll discuss the phase estimation problem and how we can solve it
with a quantum computer.

4
00:19.170 --> 00:25.980
We'll then apply phase estimation to the problem of integer factorization, which we discussed in the previous lesson.

5
00:25.980 --> 00:34.320
What we'll obtain is Shor's algorithm, which allows integers to be
factorized at polynomial cost or in polynomial time if we prefer

6
00:34.320 --> 00:39.660
to think in terms of the time required rather than the number of
elementary operations we need.

7
00:39.660 --> 00:46.295
This is the crown jewel of
quantum algorithms in some sense, and while factorized large integers

8
00:46.295 --> 00:54.990
may have limited utility for most people, it remains one of the most
compelling pieces of evidence that we have for the hypothesis that quantum computers will
offer striking advantages

9
00:54.990 --> 00:59.910
over classical computers. Here's an overview of the lesson.

10
00:59.910 --> 01:08.520
We'll start with a definition of the phase estimation problem itself, and then we'll discuss a method for solving this problem
with a quantum computer.

11
01:08.520 --> 01:14.310
We'll take it one step at a time, beginning with what you can
think of as a kind of a warmup.

12
01:14.310 --> 01:21.480
In the phase estimation problem, the goal is to approximate
a certain real number and in this warmup part
we'll see how we can get

13
01:21.480 --> 01:25.350
a very low precision
approximation to this number.

14
01:25.350 --> 01:32.310
This isn't going to be
good enough for factoring when we apply our solution to
the phase estimation problem to integer factorization,

15
01:32.310 --> 01:38.730
we're actually going to need a pretty high precision approximation, but it's nevertheless useful to begin with this sort of a warmup

16
01:38.730 --> 01:42.510
just to get a sense for
how the whole thing works.

17
01:42.510 --> 01:51.720
We'll then discuss the issue of how we can get more precision, and this will lead very
naturally to an operation known as the Quantum Fourier transform.

18
01:51.720 --> 01:57.240
We'll see exactly what this operation is and how it can be implemented
with a quantum circuit.

19
01:57.240 --> 02:06.270
And once we have it, we'll be able to apply
it to phase estimation to come up with a general procedure for solving the problem
with very high precision.

20
02:06.270 --> 02:13.680
Then in the last part of the lesson, we'll see how a solution to
the phase estimation problem allows us to factor integers efficiently.

21
02:13.680 --> 02:22.050
And specifically what we'll get is Shor's algorithm for
integer factorization, or at least something that's equivalent to Shor's algorithm.

22
02:22.050 --> 02:30.330
The way that this works is that we basically give
ourselves a stepping stone, which is yet another problem called the order finding problem.

23
02:30.330 --> 02:38.310
And in particular we'll see how we can solve the order finding problem using the phase estimation procedure and then we'll see how
we can factor integers

24
02:38.310 --> 02:45.300
by solving the order finding problem. We're going to begin with a special case of a theorem called the Spectral theorem,

25
02:45.300 --> 02:51.810
and specifically we're going to focus on what the theorem tells
us for unitary matrices.

26
02:51.810 --> 02:57.420
The spectral theorem is
a very important theorem from linear algebra and
functional analysis.

27
02:57.420 --> 03:04.800
It tells us something interesting about how certain linear mappings can be expressed in a certain form, it's often called a
spectral decomposition,

28
03:04.800 --> 03:08.700
that's useful for many reasons.

29
03:08.700 --> 03:15.300
And like I said, we're going to focus on what this theorem tells
us for unitary matrices.

30
03:15.300 --> 03:21.960
The spectral theorem is
more general than this. It doesn't work for all matrices, but it does work for a class of matrices

31
03:21.960 --> 03:28.680
called normal matrices, which include all unitary matrices as well as some matrices
that aren't unitary.

32
03:28.680 --> 03:38.490
But just to keep things simple, we'll restrict our attention
to unitary matrices for now because that's all we need for
the purposes of this lesson.

33
03:38.490 --> 03:43.890
Here's a statement of the spectral theorem just for unitary matrices.

34
03:43.890 --> 03:48.240
Suppose that U is an
N by N unitary matrix.

35
03:48.240 --> 03:54.480
What the theorem says
is that there must exist an orthonormal basis of
vectors, psi one through psi N,

36
03:54.480 --> 04:04.590
along with N complex numbers
Lambda one through Lambda N, all lying on the complex unit circle so that U can be expressed
as we have in this equation.

37
04:04.590 --> 04:12.780
This is called a spectral
decomposition of U, as I've already mentioned, and it can be very convenient to know that U can be written in this way.

38
04:12.780 --> 04:20.670
It can sometimes be convenient to have these vectors and these numbers when we're working with
a particular unitary matrix U, and it can also be very
useful simply to know

39
04:20.670 --> 04:28.050
that such an expression is always possible as a way of proving certain things about unitary matrices for instance.

40
04:28.050 --> 04:34.080
In this statement of the theorem, each of these numbers,
Lambda one through lambda N, is written in a particular way

41
04:34.080 --> 04:42.180
as E to the power two pi I times theta where each of the thetas
theta one through theta N is a real number, and
we'll come back to this way

42
04:42.180 --> 04:45.750
of writing each of these
numbers in just a little bit.

43
04:45.750 --> 04:55.830
An important thing to notice
about these vectors and numbers is that each vector psi
K must be an eigenvector of the matrix U with
corresponding eigenvalue lambda K.

44
04:55.830 --> 05:01.920
Which means that if we
multiply psi K by U, what we get is lambda K times psi K.

45
05:01.920 --> 05:09.540
So what U does to each of these vectors is simply to multiply it by the corresponding number lambda K.

46
05:09.540 --> 05:15.540
In general for some arbitrary vector, this won't be how U works, but eigenvectors are special.

47
05:15.540 --> 05:21.240
And what the theorem tells us is that there is in fact
an ortho normal basis of these eigenvectors.

48
05:21.240 --> 05:30.420
This equation down here by the way, follows from the expression that we have for U from the theorem, together with the fact that
the vectors are orthonormal.

49
05:30.420 --> 05:37.740
If you multiply the
expression of U to any psi K and use the orthonormality of the vectors, you'll get a sum in which
all of the terms are zero

50
05:37.740 --> 05:43.740
except for one of them, and the one term that we're
left with looks like this.

51
05:43.740 --> 05:46.950
Now we can define the
phase estimation problem.

52
05:46.950 --> 05:51.060
The problem is a little
bit unusual as we'll see.

53
05:51.060 --> 05:57.480
We're given two things. First, we're given the description of a unitary quantum circuit,

54
05:57.480 --> 06:03.690
that acts on N qubits
for some choice of N, and when we say that this
is a unitary circuit,

55
06:03.690 --> 06:09.930
we just mean that all of
the gates are unitary, so there are no measurements
in this circuit.

56
06:09.930 --> 06:15.150
Second, we're given an N Qubit state psi, and that's the unusual part.

57
06:15.150 --> 06:22.200
We actually have a quantum
state input for this problem, and it's a single copy of this state.

58
06:22.200 --> 06:30.990
For all the other computational problems we've talked about in this series, the input has been classical, either in the form of a string
of bits or as a black box.

59
06:30.990 --> 06:37.320
And that's not surprising because the computational
problems that we encounter in our daily lives tend to be classical,

60
06:37.320 --> 06:41.010
'cause those are the
problems we care most about.

61
06:41.010 --> 06:47.880
The way that you can
think about this problem is that it's something that appears or is likely to appear as a sub problem.

62
06:47.880 --> 06:54.030
And the phase estimation procedure we'll eventually come up with is something that we
generally use as a sub-routine

63
06:54.030 --> 07:02.280
inside of some larger computation, presumably one for a classical
problem that we care about.

64
07:02.280 --> 07:09.090
Now, this is going to be a promise problem and the state psi isn't
just any old quantum state.

65
07:09.090 --> 07:17.040
We're promised that psi is an eigenvector of whatever unitary operation U it is that the given circuit describes.

66
07:17.040 --> 07:25.260
And the goal is to find or
approximate the eigenvalue that corresponds to the eigenvector psi.

67
07:25.260 --> 07:28.950
Let's state the problem a
little bit more precisely.

68
07:28.950 --> 07:35.280
The input consists of a unitary
quantum circuit on N qubits, which can be encoded as a string of bits

69
07:35.280 --> 07:43.620
using whatever method we prefer for encoding quantum circuit descriptions, along with an N Qubit state psi.

70
07:43.620 --> 07:51.547
We can call the circuit whatever we want, but what really matters in terms of the statement of this problem is the unitary operation itself

71
07:51.547 --> 07:57.240
that's performed when the circuit is run, and that unitary operation
is described by the Matrix U.

72
07:57.240 --> 08:05.310
But we're not given U as a matrix, we're just given the description of a quantum circuit that implements U.

73
08:05.310 --> 08:10.453
The promise, as I've already stated, is that psi is an eigenvector of U.

74
08:10.453 --> 08:16.620
So if we ran our circuit on psi, we'd get psi coming out multiplied by whatever the eigenvalue is,

75
08:16.620 --> 08:21.180
which would be a global
phase in that situation.

76
08:21.180 --> 08:28.860
And finally, the output of the problem is an approximation to the eigenvalue corresponding to psi, and specifically we're looking for

77
08:28.860 --> 08:35.250
an approximation to the real number theta, between zero and one, including
zero, but not including one

78
08:35.250 --> 08:41.640
that satisfies the equation
that we have on the screen.

79
08:41.640 --> 08:49.020
To explain this way of
parameterizing the eigenvalue corresponding to pis, and also to clarify what we mean by an approximation,

80
08:49.020 --> 08:52.920
let's draw a picture of
the complex unit circle.

81
08:52.920 --> 08:59.100
We can put the numbers one, I,
negative one, and negative I in their usual places and we can consider

82
08:59.100 --> 09:06.570
some arbitrary point on the
circle parameterized by theta as we have in the problem statement.

83
09:06.570 --> 09:15.877
This is the point we
get if we start at one and rotate by an angle of
two times pi times theta, so the angle isn't
theta, it's two pi theta,

84
09:15.877 --> 09:22.710
and another way of thinking about it is that if we start at one and we travel a distance of two pi theta on the circle itself,

85
09:22.710 --> 09:27.570
we'll get to our point, E to
the two times pi times theta.

86
09:27.570 --> 09:33.060
Every point in the complex unit circle can be represented in this way
for a unique choice of theta.

87
09:33.060 --> 09:39.510
And that's because we go
all the way around circle as theta goes from zero to one, and if we went all the
way to theta equals one,

88
09:39.510 --> 09:45.180
we'd be back where we
started at theta equals zero, so that's why we include zero, but we don't include one.

89
09:45.180 --> 09:54.240
Just to make sure that each
point on the complex unit circle corresponds to a unique value of theta in the range that we're considering.

90
09:54.240 --> 10:01.860
There are various ways
that we could imagine approximating a particular value of theta, but the way that we'll do it is to approximate theta with a fraction,

91
10:01.860 --> 10:09.660
where the denominator
is two to the power M for some choice of a positive integer M, and the numerator is an integer y

92
10:09.660 --> 10:14.040
between zero and two to the M minus one.

93
10:14.040 --> 10:20.670
You can think about this as an mbit approximation to theta if you wish, and we could write this
number in binary notation

94
10:20.670 --> 10:25.800
where we have a binary point followed by the binary
representation of Y.

95
10:25.800 --> 10:35.160
I say binary point by the
way rather than decimal point because decimal means base 10 and I'm talking about base two
here, but it's the same idea.

96
10:35.160 --> 10:40.980
But in any case we can
also just think about it as a fraction like it
appears on the screen.

97
10:40.980 --> 10:47.010
And to be clear, when we think about
approximations in this context, it should be understood
that values of theta

98
10:47.010 --> 10:51.510
near zero and values of theta near one are in fact close together.

99
10:51.510 --> 10:58.440
So for example, if theta is equal to 0.99 and we approximate this value
of theta by the value zero,

100
10:58.440 --> 11:04.950
then that's a pretty good approximation in the sense that it's
within one of our hundred of the actual value, when
we wrap around the circle

101
11:04.950 --> 11:08.340
and go back to zero when we get to one.

102
11:08.340 --> 11:16.980
The term modular one is sometimes used to describe the situation, where we're essentially
equating theta equals one with theta equals zero.

103
11:16.980 --> 11:23.010
The point is that we really care about the location of the point
E to the two pi I theta on the unit circle,

104
11:23.010 --> 11:29.490
and thinking about this
way of approximating theta makes sense when we have that aim in mind.

105
11:29.490 --> 11:36.270
The problem statement itself,
as it appears on the screen, isn't specific about how good the approximation to theta needs to be,

106
11:36.270 --> 11:41.130
but that's something that we can fine tune depending upon our needs.

107
11:41.130 --> 11:47.610
In some situations we might be satisfied with a low precision
approximation to theta, and in other situations we might demand

108
11:47.610 --> 11:53.550
a very high precision approximation, and the problem statement itself
can be refined accordingly.

109
11:53.550 --> 12:00.930
Next we'll see how we can solve
the phase estimation problem with a quantum computer and
we'll start with a warmup.

110
12:00.930 --> 12:03.930
This won't be our final
solution to the problem.

111
12:03.930 --> 12:14.130
What we'll do is to make use of the phase kickback phenomenon to try to learn something
about the eigenvalue corresponding to a given eigenvector.

112
12:14.130 --> 12:21.240
Recall that in the
phase estimation problem we're given the description
of a unitary quantum circuit for some operation U,

113
12:21.240 --> 12:30.600
and what we do first is to
use this circuit description to create a new circuit that implements a controlled U operation like
is pictured on the screen.

114
12:30.600 --> 12:37.230
This is pretty simple to do. What we can do is to add a control Qubit, which is pictured on
the top in this diagram

115
12:37.230 --> 12:43.460
and use this new control
Qubit as a control for every single gate that
appears in our circuit.

116
12:43.460 --> 12:50.760
So all of the gates are applied if this control Qubit is set to one, and none of them is applied if the control Qubit is set to zero,

117
12:50.760 --> 12:57.960
That means that we're going
to need a controlled version of every gate that
appears in the circuit U, but we don't need to think
about these new controlled gates

118
12:57.960 --> 13:04.440
as single gates if we don't want to. They could be implemented
as small circuits made out of gates from whatever gates set

119
13:04.440 --> 13:12.270
we've chosen to use. And once we have a
controlled version of U, we can consider running this circuit,

120
13:12.270 --> 13:20.310
where we first put the control Qubit into a superposition of zero and one, apply the controlled U gate to the eigenvector side that we're given,

121
13:20.310 --> 13:25.290
and then apply a Hadamard gate
to the control and measure.

122
13:25.290 --> 13:32.730
We'll see why it makes sense to do this as we go through the analysis, but even before we get to the details, we can immediately see a similarity

123
13:32.730 --> 13:40.200
with Deutsche's algorithm for instance, where we're applying a
couple of Hadamard gates and measuring as a way
of effectively probing

124
13:40.200 --> 13:43.920
what it is that some given
operation is doing here.

125
13:43.920 --> 13:51.240
It's a controlled unitary
rather than a query gate, but there are very similar ideas at play.

126
13:51.240 --> 13:56.010
So let's see what the circuit does.

127
13:56.010 --> 14:02.400
The initial state is the eigenvector psi, tensored with the zero
state for the control Qubit,

128
14:02.400 --> 14:13.903
applying the first Hadamard gate transforms the state of the
top Qubit to a plus state and we can expand the entire
state as is shown right here.

129
14:13.903 --> 14:21.480
We then apply the controlled U operation and what that does is to apply U to psi when the control Qubit is set to one,

130
14:21.480 --> 14:27.780
but not when it's set to zero. So we get the state pi two
that's written on the screen.

131
14:27.780 --> 14:34.950
We can simplify the state
using the fact that psi is an eigenvector of U with eigenvalue e to the two pi I theta.

132
14:34.950 --> 14:39.810
So we get that eigenvalue multiplying the second
term, but not the first.

133
14:39.810 --> 14:44.910
And we can simplify using the bilinearity
of the tensor product.

134
14:44.910 --> 14:53.550
So what we have here is the
phase kickback phenomenon, but this time it's happening for some arbitrary eigenvector psi of some arbitrary unitary operation U,

135
14:53.550 --> 15:00.600
s opposed to a not operation being applied to a minus
state more specifically.

136
15:00.600 --> 15:04.950
So that's the state after the controlled U operation is applied.

137
15:04.950 --> 15:11.880
By the way, it's worth
taking a moment to notice that the state of the bottom end Qubits is still the eigenvector psi.

138
15:11.880 --> 15:18.150
Which is great because that
gives us the opportunity to use it again if we choose.

139
15:18.150 --> 15:23.010
Then the second Hadamard gate is performed and here is the state that we get.

140
15:23.010 --> 15:30.090
And I haven't shown all the
details of the derivation here, but if you apply the
Hadamard gate and simplify, this is what you should get.

141
15:30.090 --> 15:34.770
So that's the state just
prior to the measurement.

142
15:34.770 --> 15:39.750
So we can focus on this state to see what we can learn
about theta by measuring.

143
15:39.750 --> 15:46.080
And if we measure the top
Qubit or the rightmost Qubit, these are the probabilities that we get for the two outcomes.

144
15:46.080 --> 15:52.950
And here have used a
couple of basic formulas that relate sins and cosines
to complex exponentials to express these probabilities

145
15:52.950 --> 15:56.310
in terms of sins and cosines.

146
15:56.310 --> 16:02.670
Specifically, the probability to get zero is the cosine squared of pi times theta and the probability to get one

147
16:02.670 --> 16:10.950
is the sin squared of the same angle. And this makes sense
because the sin squared plus the cosine squared of
any angle is equal to one.

148
16:10.950 --> 16:16.380
So our probabilities
sum to one as we expect.

149
16:16.380 --> 16:21.750
And here is a plot of these probabilities as a function of theta.

150
16:21.750 --> 16:30.810
To be clear, this is a plot of
the probabilities themselves as opposed to a plot depicting a single probability
distribution for instance.

151
16:30.810 --> 16:38.310
For example, if theta
is equal to one half, then the probability that
we get the outcome one which is drawn in purple is equal to one

152
16:38.310 --> 16:44.190
while the probability
to get the outcome zero, which is drawn in blue, is zero.

153
16:44.190 --> 16:52.020
On the other hand, if theta is equal to one
quarter or three quarters, then we have that each of the two outcomes is equally likely.

154
16:52.020 --> 16:59.040
And of course for all choices of theta, the sum of the probabilities is equal to one as we've already observed.

155
16:59.040 --> 17:05.850
So we don't learn exactly what
theta is from this procedure, but it does give us some
information about theta.

156
17:05.850 --> 17:13.050
And if we imagine a situation in which we're promised
that theta is equal to zero or theta is equal to one half, this procedure will tell us

157
17:13.050 --> 17:17.250
exactly which one of the
two possibilities it is.

158
17:17.250 --> 17:24.630
So that's a simple way that we can use the phase kickback phenomenon to learn something about the eigenvalue.

159
17:24.630 --> 17:27.690
So how can we learn more
about the eigenvalue?

160
17:27.690 --> 17:31.800
Well, this is a situation in which we can let
ignorance be our guide.

161
17:31.800 --> 17:35.520
Because there really aren't
too many things that we can do.

162
17:35.520 --> 17:41.910
We don't know much of anything
about the eigenvector sin, and we also don't know
much about the operation U.

163
17:41.910 --> 17:50.040
We have a circuit for U, but for all we know it's
a horrible, confusing mess that we won't be able to make
any sense of by examining it.

164
17:50.040 --> 17:54.450
But one natural option is to run the circuit multiple times.

165
17:54.450 --> 18:02.820
In particular, we could try to do exactly the same thing that we just did, except that instead of applying just a single controlled U operation,

166
18:02.820 --> 18:10.920
we apply that operation twice. Or we could apply it any number of times, but let's start with twice
just to see what happens.

167
18:10.920 --> 18:19.290
Well, it's actually pretty
simple what happens. By applying the controlled
U operation twice, we're effectively just
squaring the eigenvalue

168
18:19.290 --> 18:24.866
because it'll get kicked into
the phase of the top Qubit two times rather than just once.

169
18:24.866 --> 18:32.760
And so when we think about
the outcome probabilities as a function of theta, we're essentially just
doubling the frequency.

170
18:32.760 --> 18:39.870
For each possible choice of theta, the outcome probabilities
are the same as they would be if we doubled theta and then
took the fractional part

171
18:39.870 --> 18:43.680
to get a number between zero and one.

172
18:43.680 --> 18:48.390
For example, if theta
is equal to one half, then the eigenvalue is negative one.

173
18:48.390 --> 18:55.740
So by applying U twice we're effectively squaring the eigenvalue and the result is the same as it would be for theta equals zero.

174
18:55.740 --> 19:05.580
Which is that the probability
for the outcome zero, pictured in blue, is equal to one, and the probability for the outcome one, pictured in purple, is equal to zero.

175
19:05.580 --> 19:11.700
This is very simple, but we can in fact get
some additional information about theta by doing this.

176
19:11.700 --> 19:18.630
For example, if we know in advance that either theta is equal to zero or theta equals one quarter, then this circuit will reveal to us

177
19:18.630 --> 19:22.020
which of the two possibilities it is.

178
19:22.020 --> 19:28.410
On the other hand, we can no longer distinguish the case that theta is equal to zero from the case that theta equals one half.

179
19:28.410 --> 19:36.900
So this procedure isn't strictly better than the one from before when
we had a single control U gate but by also running this circuit

180
19:36.900 --> 19:40.170
we can gain additional information.

181
19:40.170 --> 19:46.650
It's not immediately clear
how the additional information we can get by iterating the controlled U operation multiple times

182
19:46.650 --> 19:54.360
can be reconciled with
the information we get by performing it just once, and in fact there are multiple
ways we could proceed.

183
19:54.360 --> 20:00.930
For instance, there's a technique called iterative phase estimation, which involves running circuits like the ones that we've seen,

184
20:00.930 --> 20:06.930
along with some minor variations on them, to come up with an approximation to theta.

185
20:06.930 --> 20:14.730
But I'm gonna describe
what could be called a more traditional approach, where we use a single quantum circuit that has multiple control qubits

186
20:14.730 --> 20:20.850
that control different
numbers of iterations of the unitary operation U.

187
20:20.850 --> 20:28.800
First I'll describe how this
works for two control qubits and then a bit later we'll generalize it to more than two control qubits.

188
20:28.800 --> 20:31.950
Here's a quantum circuit
that uses two control qubits.

189
20:31.950 --> 20:38.880
The top control Qubit
controls a single U operation while the second from top
Qubit controls two copies of U.

190
20:38.880 --> 20:45.840
So what we're doing is combining the two circuits that we saw previously, in a way that makes use of the single copy

191
20:45.840 --> 20:49.500
of the eigenvector psi that we have.

192
20:49.500 --> 20:57.240
You'll notice however
that the Hadamard gates after the controlled U
operations have been removed and there are no measurements yet.

193
20:57.240 --> 21:03.990
What we're going to do is to
see how this circuit works and then we'll figure
out what we should do with the top two qubits

194
21:03.990 --> 21:11.610
in order to learn as much as possible about the value theta that
we're trying to approximate.

195
21:11.610 --> 21:16.656
After the Hadamard gates performed, we had the state that's
shown on the screen.

196
21:16.656 --> 21:21.570
And this is going to be a convenient way of writing the state to
see what happens next.

197
21:21.570 --> 21:27.780
A zero and A one are bits, and if we think about the top two qubits as being a two Qubit register,

198
21:27.780 --> 21:36.690
we're thinking about A zero, which corresponds to the top Qubit as being the lesser significant bit, and A one which corresponds
to the lower control Qubit

199
21:36.690 --> 21:40.590
as being the more significant bit.

200
21:40.590 --> 21:45.630
After the first controlled
U operation is performed, we obtain this state.

201
21:45.630 --> 21:52.198
The classical state corresponding to the top control Qubit is a zero, so the result of the phase kickback

202
21:52.198 --> 21:59.190
can be expressed in this way. Then after the second and
third controlled U operations

203
21:59.190 --> 22:02.220
are performed, we obtain this state.

204
22:02.220 --> 22:08.490
The idea is the same as for the first one, except this time we're applying the control U operation twice.

205
22:08.490 --> 22:15.681
So we multiply A one by two in
the exponent to reflect this.

206
22:15.681 --> 22:25.620
And now we can simplify this expression by thinking about the bits
A one and A zero together as an integer between zero and
three using binary notation.

207
22:25.620 --> 22:32.100
That is when we think
about the two bit string, A one A zero, as the binary
encoding of an integer,

208
22:32.100 --> 22:35.670
what we get is two
times A one plus A zero.

209
22:35.670 --> 22:44.100
And the understanding is
that when we write Cat X, we're talking about X written as a binary string of length
too using binary notation.

210
22:44.100 --> 22:50.430
So now let's focus on
these two control qubits to figure out what we
can learn about theta from them at this point.

211
22:50.430 --> 22:58.498
The remaining N qubits are
still in the same state psi that we were originally given, which is really a wonderful
thing about this approach

212
22:58.498 --> 23:03.720
because like I said before, we can use that state again if we want to gain even more
information about theta.

213
23:03.720 --> 23:10.530
But for now, let's just think about what we can learn from
these two control qubits.

214
23:10.530 --> 23:16.710
To help us to figure out how to proceed, let's imagine that we're promised that theta is equal to Y over four

215
23:16.710 --> 23:20.790
for some integer y between zero and three.

216
23:20.790 --> 23:26.850
In general, theta may not
be one of these four values, but this is a natural case to consider.

217
23:26.850 --> 23:33.960
We saw in the original single control Qubit version of the procedure that if we were promised that theta is either zero or one half

218
23:33.960 --> 23:40.680
the circuit would reveal which one it was. And we also noticed that in the version where we applied the
controlled U operation twice,

219
23:40.680 --> 23:46.440
we could perfectly discriminate the case that theta equals zero from the case that theta
equals one quarter.

220
23:46.440 --> 23:52.710
So we might hope that with our new circuit we can discriminate these four cases.

221
23:52.710 --> 24:00.870
In essence, what we're
doing is that we're using the notion of a promise problem
to make the problem easier, so that we can see how to proceed.

222
24:00.870 --> 24:08.400
And that's not a bad idea, in general. If you have a problem and you
don't know how to solve it, try making it easier.

223
24:08.400 --> 24:14.310
If you can solve the easier problem, the insight you gain might be helpful in solving the more general problem.

224
24:14.310 --> 24:18.690
And if you can't solve the easier problem, you're probably not ready
for the more general problem.

225
24:18.690 --> 24:23.220
So keep on making it easier
until you can solve it.

226
24:23.220 --> 24:30.780
Anyway, getting back to our problem, let's define a two Qubit state for each of the possible values of Y.

227
24:30.780 --> 24:39.780
In other words, phi Y is equal to the state
shown on the top of the screen when theta is chosen
specifically to be Y over four.

228
24:39.780 --> 24:43.800
And here are those four
states written out explicitly.

229
24:43.800 --> 24:52.230
So just to reiterate, if
theta is equal to Y over four for Y being zero, one, two, or
three and we run our circuit,

230
24:52.230 --> 24:59.474
we're going to be left with
one of these four states, whichever one corresponds
to the right value of Y.

231
24:59.474 --> 25:02.520
And we just wanna figure
out which one it is.

232
25:02.520 --> 25:05.670
And the question is, is this possible?

233
25:05.670 --> 25:11.280
And the answer to that question is yes, because these four states are orthogonal.

234
25:11.280 --> 25:16.020
If you compute the inner product
between any pair of them, you'll get zero.

235
25:16.020 --> 25:23.250
And because they're orthogonal, they can be perfectly discriminated by a projective measurement.

236
25:23.250 --> 25:30.240
And in particular we can
express such a measurement by defining one projection for each vector like we have here.

237
25:30.240 --> 25:38.190
This always works, anytime
we have an orthonormal basis, and you can check this
against the definitions we saw in lesson three
for this specific case

238
25:38.190 --> 25:45.210
if you're so inclined. So we conclude that it is
possible to accomplish our task,

239
25:45.210 --> 25:50.670
which is to learn the value of Y from the state that's shown
on the top of the screen.

240
25:50.670 --> 25:55.830
And if we'd like to do that
with a quantum circuit, we can proceed as I'll now explain.

241
25:55.830 --> 26:02.640
First we can define a unitary matrix V whose columns are the four
vectors listed in order.

242
26:02.640 --> 26:08.640
That matrix will have the action described on the bottom of the screen,
on the standard basis states,

243
26:08.640 --> 26:14.070
and we can write down the matrix
to see what it looks like.

244
26:14.070 --> 26:20.760
Because V maps each standard basis state, kappa Y to the vector phi Y, we have that by applying V dagger,

245
26:20.760 --> 26:28.830
or in other words V inverse to phi Y will transform back the other way to the corresponding standard basis state.

246
26:28.830 --> 26:34.380
So what we can do is to apply V dagger to whatever state we
obtained from our circuit.

247
26:34.380 --> 26:43.890
And then if we perform a
standard basis measurement, we'll get the number Y
that we're looking for, expressed as a string
of length two in binary.

248
26:43.890 --> 26:49.500
Before we go any further, let's talk a bit more
about the unitary matrix V.

249
26:49.500 --> 26:53.790
This is a special matrix and
you may have seen it before.

250
26:53.790 --> 27:01.440
It's the matrix associated
with a linear operation on four dimensional vectors known as the discrete Fourier transform.

251
27:01.440 --> 27:10.230
To be more precise, the discrete Fourier transform can be defined for any
positive integer dimension, and we'll take a look at it
in general in a few moments.

252
27:10.230 --> 27:15.900
And this is what it
looks like specifically when the dimension is equal to four.

253
27:15.900 --> 27:19.950
We can think about the
discrete Fourier transform in different ways.

254
27:19.950 --> 27:28.245
We can think about it purely abstractly as a linear mapping on vectors that can be represented by a matrix.

255
27:28.245 --> 27:34.710
And we can also think about
it as a computational problem where we're given a vector, and we want to compute the result

256
27:34.710 --> 27:39.630
of applying this linear mapping.

257
27:39.630 --> 27:46.560
That turns out to be an incredibly important
computational problem, and there's a highly efficient algorithm for performing that computation

258
27:46.560 --> 27:50.100
known as the fasts Fourier transform.

259
27:50.100 --> 27:57.990
In fact, this is such an important problem in signal processing for example, that the fasts Fourier
transform is considered by many

260
27:57.990 --> 28:03.030
to be one of the most important and consequential
algorithms ever discovered.

261
28:03.030 --> 28:10.410
We can also think about the
discrete Fourier transform as a unitary quantum operation that can be applied to
a quantum state vector.

262
28:10.410 --> 28:18.000
And when we think about it in that way, we call it the quantum Fourier
transform, or QFT for short.

263
28:18.000 --> 28:24.810
Mathematically speaking, it's essentially the same thing as the discrete Fourier transform, but we call it the
quantum Fourier transform

264
28:24.810 --> 28:30.390
just to clarify that it's an operation being applied to a quantum state vector.

265
28:30.390 --> 28:36.810
So let's change the name of our matrix, from V to QFT four to reflect the fact

266
28:36.810 --> 28:43.410
that the operation that we've come up with is in fact the quantum Fourier transform.

267
28:43.410 --> 28:49.920
So here's the complete circuit for learning the value of Y when we're promised that
theta equals Y over four

268
28:49.920 --> 28:53.640
for Y being zero, one, two, or three.

269
28:53.640 --> 29:00.720
And just to make sure it's clear, we're applying the inverse of
the quantum Fourier transform, or in other words QFT four dagger

270
29:00.720 --> 29:10.200
to map one of the four possible states back to the standard basis state, cat Y, so that we can recover Y by measuring.

271
29:10.200 --> 29:17.100
So that's the circuit we
get from thinking about the promised version of the
phase estimation problem, where we're promised that theta

272
29:17.100 --> 29:23.130
is zero, one quarter, one
half, or three quarters, but there's nothing that prevents us

273
29:23.130 --> 29:28.620
from running this circuit for
an arbitrary value of theta.

274
29:28.620 --> 29:35.130
And if we do that, here
are the probabilities for the four possible
outcomes that we obtain.

275
29:35.130 --> 29:43.920
Each of the four possible
values for Y has its own color, and the plot tells us
what the probabilities are for each one as a function of theta.

276
29:43.920 --> 29:50.280
So for instance, if theta
is equal to three quarters, we'll get the outcome
three with probability one,

277
29:50.280 --> 29:58.530
well the probabilities for the other three outcomes are all zero as we already know from thinking about the promise version of the problem.

278
29:58.530 --> 30:06.240
If theta is close to three quarters but not exactly three quarters, there will be some non-zero probability associated with the other outcomes,

279
30:06.240 --> 30:10.110
but we'll still get the outcome
three with high probability.

280
30:10.110 --> 30:17.550
So even though theta may
not be equal to Y over four, we can still think
about the outcome we get from the measurements divided by four

281
30:17.550 --> 30:21.630
as being a guess or an
approximation for theta.

282
30:21.630 --> 30:27.570
The guess may be wrong, but nevertheless it is
providing us with information.

283
30:27.570 --> 30:36.060
And one thing that we
can learn from the plot is that best approximations always have the highest
probabilities associated with them.

284
30:36.060 --> 30:43.452
When I say best approximation, I mean whatever value of Y over four is closest to the true value of theta,

285
30:43.452 --> 30:51.840
in the modular one sense. The worst possible case is that theta is exactly halfway between
two values of Y over four.

286
30:51.840 --> 30:59.850
For example, if theta is equal
to three eighths or 0.375, in this case we see
that the approximations

287
30:59.850 --> 31:03.930
one quarter and two quarters
or one half are equally good.

288
31:03.930 --> 31:08.854
So in this particular
case there are actually two best approximations rather than one.

289
31:08.854 --> 31:12.360
And we're equally likely to get the outcome one
and the outcome two.

290
31:12.360 --> 31:20.400
The other two outcomes zero and three, which don't give very good
approximations to theta when we divide by four, actually do appear with some probability

291
31:20.400 --> 31:24.840
which appears to be just
under 10% in both cases.

292
31:24.840 --> 31:30.180
So this procedure isn't perfect, but it does provide us with information.

293
31:30.180 --> 31:36.390
And it's noteworthy that
regardless of theta, we're always guaranteed to draw either the best approximation

294
31:36.390 --> 31:44.250
or one of the two best approximations when there's a tie, with probability that
appears to be just above 40%.

295
31:44.250 --> 31:50.910
And the closer that theta
is to the approximation, the higher the probability to see the corresponding value of Y.

296
31:50.910 --> 31:56.040
And that's a pretty
significant improvement over using a single control Qubit.

297
31:56.040 --> 32:02.220
This is in fact the phase
estimation procedure when we choose to use two control qubits.

298
32:02.220 --> 32:08.820
And what we'll do next is to generalize this
procedure in a natural way, where we don't stop with
just two control qubits

299
32:08.820 --> 32:12.450
but we use however many
control qubits we choose.

300
32:12.450 --> 32:18.960
And what we'll see is that by
generalizing the procedure, by adding more control qubits, we'll be able to get more and more

301
32:18.960 --> 32:26.615
accurate approximations of theta. And that will be the general
phase estimation procedure.

302
32:26.615 --> 32:33.660
In order to generalize the
phase estimation procedure from two control qubits
to however many we choose, we're going to need to understand

303
32:33.660 --> 32:37.920
how the quantum Fourier transform is defined for other dimensions.

304
32:37.920 --> 32:42.690
And we're also gonna need to discuss how it can be implemented
with a quantum circuit.

305
32:42.690 --> 32:49.800
Here's the definition of the
quantum Fourier transform when the dimension is an
arbitrary positive integer N.

306
32:49.800 --> 32:57.570
Here we're thinking about this operation as being an operation on a system whose classical states are
zero up to N minus one.

307
32:57.570 --> 33:04.980
And here the matrix that
describes this operation has been expressed using
the direct notation.

308
33:04.980 --> 33:14.190
We can also describe it in terms of its action
on standard basis states, just to connect it with
what we already saw when N is equal to four.

309
33:14.190 --> 33:19.915
So here's what it looks
like when N is equal to one, which isn't a very interesting case.

310
33:19.915 --> 33:28.302
Here it is for N is equal to two, and you'll notice what we get in this case is a Hadamard operation.

311
33:28.302 --> 33:31.560
Here's the quantum Fourier
transform for N equals three.

312
33:31.560 --> 33:36.122
For N equals four, which
we've already seen.

313
33:36.122 --> 33:41.220
And for one last example, here it is when N is equal to eight.

314
33:41.220 --> 33:47.700
Just like we had before
for the N equals four case, These are the matrices that we associate with the discrete Fourier transform

315
33:47.700 --> 33:56.340
for each of the dimensions. But we call it the
quantum Fourier transform when we want to think about
it as a quantum operation.

316
33:56.340 --> 34:04.110
Sometimes by the way, the leading factor of one over the square root of N is not included when we think about the discrete Fourier
transform as a matrix,

317
34:04.110 --> 34:09.540
but we need that factor here to make sure that we get a unitary matrix.

318
34:09.540 --> 34:14.250
There's also sometimes a minus sign in each of the exponents, but not always.

319
34:14.250 --> 34:20.490
It's basically just a personal preference that doesn't change the fundamental
nature of the transform.

320
34:20.490 --> 34:29.790
But in any case, we'll define the quantum Fourier transform as it's written here on the screen.

321
34:29.790 --> 34:35.610
There's a very useful shorthand
notation that's common and we'll make use of it
a bit later in the lesson.

322
34:35.610 --> 34:40.950
And that is to define a
complex number omega N, like we have here.

323
34:40.950 --> 34:47.500
Specifically as e to the two pi I over N, which can also be written
using signs and cosines

324
34:47.500 --> 34:56.910
as we have right here. Sometimes we call this
number an N through of unity because when we raise it
to the power N, we get one.

325
34:56.910 --> 35:00.330
Here's a figure that shows a few examples.

326
35:00.330 --> 35:08.160
Omega one is equal to one, omega two is equal to negative one, and omega four is equal to I.

327
35:08.160 --> 35:17.010
In general to get omega N, we can imagine slicing up the unit circle into N equal size pieces like it's a pizza being shared by N people

328
35:17.010 --> 35:23.220
and omega N is at the
corner of the first piece, assuming that the other corner
of that piece is at one.

329
35:23.220 --> 35:32.430
So in particular as N
gets larger and larger, the pieces will get smaller and smaller, and omega N will get
closer and closer to one.

330
35:32.430 --> 35:38.970
And now if we use that notation we can express the
quantum Fourier transform in a slightly cleaner way.

331
35:38.970 --> 35:45.330
Sometimes this notation
helps to keep things simple as we will see happening
a bit later in the lesson.

332
35:45.330 --> 35:51.390
There's an efficient quantum
circuit implementation of the quantum Fourier transform
when N is a power of two,

333
35:51.390 --> 35:58.860
which we'll now take a look at. Although we tend define the
quantum Fourier transform for any dimension N,
we're only gonna need it

334
35:58.860 --> 36:05.940
in the case that N is a power of two, in order to generalize the
phase estimation procedure.

335
36:05.940 --> 36:12.930
The implementation will make
use of controlled phase gauge which are depicted as we
have here on the screen.

336
36:12.930 --> 36:18.330
They look like two
controls connected together along with a number which
is alpha in this case.

337
36:18.330 --> 36:23.490
And the action of this gate is described by the matrix that's shown here.

338
36:23.490 --> 36:30.090
These are literally
controlled phase gates, meaning that we have a control Qubit that controls a phase gate.

339
36:30.090 --> 36:33.090
We saw phase gates way back in lesson one.

340
36:33.090 --> 36:38.670
But for phase gates specifically, it doesn't actually matter
which Qubit is the control and which is the target.

341
36:38.670 --> 36:44.340
And we saw that in lesson two, for the specific case of a Z gate.

342
36:44.340 --> 36:51.330
And now that we have that notion, we can move on to how the
quantum Fourier transform can be implemented.

343
36:51.330 --> 37:01.500
The implementation is recursive in nature and perhaps the easiest way
to describe it in simple terms is to give an example that
can easily be generalized.

344
37:01.500 --> 37:04.620
Here's how we can do it
when N is equal to 32.

345
37:04.620 --> 37:07.680
So there are five qubits.

346
37:07.680 --> 37:17.130
To be clear, we're associating the
standard basis states of these five qubits with the integers between zero and 31 using binary notation.

347
37:17.130 --> 37:24.570
The first thing we do is to perform the quantum Fourier
transform for N equals 16 to all of the qubits except for
the least significant Qubit,

348
37:24.570 --> 37:29.400
which is the one on the top. And that's the recursive
part of the construction.

349
37:29.400 --> 37:34.920
So to implement this operation, we have to follow the same
pattern but with one fewer Qubit.

350
37:34.920 --> 37:42.660
And in the base case we
have just a single Qubit for which the quantum Fourier transform is just a Hadamard gate.

351
37:42.660 --> 37:52.590
Once we apply the QFT on all of the qubits except for the top one, we apply a bunch of controlled phase gates using the phases that are
indicated in the diagram.

352
37:52.590 --> 37:59.490
We then apply a Hadamard
gate to the top Qubit, and shuffle the qubits around a little bit using some swap gates.

353
37:59.490 --> 38:07.080
These swap gates have the effect of cyclically permuting the qubits which is needed to make
the construction work.

354
38:07.080 --> 38:14.010
We can follow exactly the same pattern for other choices of N
provided they're powers of two, where we always start the
controlled phase gates

355
38:14.010 --> 38:20.370
with alpha being pi over
two for the bottom Qubit and dividing by two each time
moving left in the diagram

356
38:20.370 --> 38:27.060
to get the subsequent phases. Now it's not at all obvious
that this construction works.

357
38:27.060 --> 38:30.690
And I'm not gonna explain
why it works in this video.

358
38:30.690 --> 38:36.990
If you're interested in seeing
the details for why it works, you can find them in the
written content for the lesson.

359
38:36.990 --> 38:43.020
I will say however that
what's being exploited here is the basic structure of
discrete Fourier transforms

360
38:43.020 --> 38:49.320
and in fact it's exactly
the same structure that allows the fast
Fourier transform to work.

361
38:49.320 --> 38:55.530
Another way to say this is that if we look at the fast Fourier transform, we can think about it in
terms of quantum circuits.

362
38:55.530 --> 39:00.000
And this is the circuit that we get.

363
39:00.000 --> 39:06.030
So how many gates do we need in total for this implementation?

364
39:06.030 --> 39:13.380
To figure that out, let's let SM be the number of gates that
we need when we have M qubits.

365
39:13.380 --> 39:20.730
When M is equal to one, we just need a single gate because the QFT is just a Hadamard operation in this case.

366
39:20.730 --> 39:25.830
If M is at least two, then these
are the gates that we need.

367
39:25.830 --> 39:35.370
First we need SM minus one gates for the quantum Fourier
transform on M minus one qubits, whatever that number happens to be.

368
39:35.370 --> 39:43.710
We also need M minus one
controlled phase gates, M minus one swap gates,

369
39:43.710 --> 39:48.930
and one additional Hadamard gate.

370
39:48.930 --> 39:59.160
So here's an expression
of SM in both cases when M is equal to one and
when M is at least two.

371
39:59.160 --> 40:06.660
This is an example of what's called a recurrence relation and
they show up very commonly in the analysis of algorithms.

372
40:06.660 --> 40:15.480
This particular one
happens to be very simple and it has a so-called
closed form expression, which we can obtain by summing.

373
40:15.480 --> 40:22.530
To be precise, the value of SM is the sum of the first M
consecutive odd integers, which equals M squared,

374
40:22.530 --> 40:27.720
as you may have either encountered before or maybe you just noticed that
at some point in your life.

375
40:27.720 --> 40:35.070
And it happens to be pretty easy to prove this formula is true by induction on M in
case you're interested in a formal proof.

376
40:35.070 --> 40:43.140
So that's it. We can implement the
quantum Fourier transform on M qubits using M squared gates.

377
40:43.140 --> 40:46.950
Just a couple of very
quick additional remarks.

378
40:46.950 --> 40:50.730
First we don't actually
need all of the swap gates that I've described.

379
40:50.730 --> 40:58.410
It is possible to effectively
push them all out to the end as long as we adjust which qubits the controlled phase gates
act on appropriately.

380
40:58.410 --> 41:04.530
And if we do that we'll only
need M over two swap gates in total rounding down.

381
41:04.530 --> 41:11.250
We'll still have a quadratic cost, but the number of gates can be reduced in this way nevertheless.

382
41:11.250 --> 41:19.140
And one final remark is that we can actually make the cost even less if we're willing to settle for
a pretty good approximation.

383
41:19.140 --> 41:25.440
For example, when M gets large, a lot of the controlled phase gates are pretty close to
the identity operation,

384
41:25.440 --> 41:34.054
and eliminating the
ones that are very close can save us quite a lot on gates while still giving us a
pretty good approximation.

385
41:34.054 --> 41:41.820
It is also possible to approximate the quantum Fourier transform
with very shallow circuits, meaning ones with small depth, in case that's something
that we wish to do.

386
41:41.820 --> 41:49.770
And now that we know what the
quantum Fourier transform is for different dimensions, as well as how it can be implemented w hen the dimension is a power of two,

387
41:49.770 --> 42:00.000
we can go back to the
phase estimation procedure and see how it can be generalized where we use some arbitrary
number M of control qubits.

388
42:00.000 --> 42:05.670
Here's what the procedure looks like as a quantum circuit for
an arbitrary choice of M.

389
42:05.670 --> 42:10.800
We have M control qubits on top, which we assume are all
initialized to the zero state.

390
42:10.800 --> 42:19.650
We apply a Hadamard
gate to each one of them and then each of them is
used as a control Qubit to apply some power of
the unitary operation U,

391
42:19.650 --> 42:23.880
where we double the number
of times U is applied for each control Qubit.

392
42:23.880 --> 42:30.600
Here in this diagram I've indicated this by including the powers
on U inside of the boxes rather than showing the controlled U gate

393
42:30.600 --> 42:39.270
being applied that many times, as a way of both making
the diagram more clear and saving on space so
that it fits on the screen.

394
42:39.270 --> 42:45.810
Now the first thing that we need to notice
about this procedure is that it might become very expensive.

395
42:45.810 --> 42:51.840
In particular we're
doubling the number of times each U operation gets applied
for each control Qubit.

396
42:51.840 --> 42:57.870
And if the way that we do this is simply to iterate a controlled U gate however many times we need,

397
42:57.870 --> 43:03.150
we're going to get a huge circuit. It'll be exponentially
large in the number M.

398
43:03.150 --> 43:11.550
That's a major limitation in general, and in particular it limits our ability to get precise approximations
of eigenvalues.

399
43:11.550 --> 43:18.660
In the specific case of factoring though, which we'll get to shortly, it turns out that we're very fortunate and we can play a trick that allows us

400
43:18.660 --> 43:21.720
to avoid this exponential blow up in cost.

401
43:21.720 --> 43:28.080
But in general for arbitrary
unitary operations U, this won't be possible and
we'll pay a steep price

402
43:28.080 --> 43:32.940
for increasing the
number of control qubits.

403
43:32.940 --> 43:40.620
I'm not going to go
through a detailed analysis of the circuit in this video and instead I'll just mention that there is a fairly simple
expression for the state

404
43:40.620 --> 43:45.870
just prior to the measurements which is shown here on the screen.

405
43:45.870 --> 43:52.530
From that state we can get an expression for the probabilities
of the various outcomes, and it happens to look like this.

406
43:52.530 --> 44:00.300
And once we have this expression,
we can reason about it, and really this expression
is all we need to carry on.

407
44:00.300 --> 44:08.820
Like I said, I'm not gonna get into
the details in this video, but you can find them in the
written content for the lesson and it turns out that it's
actually not that complicated,

408
44:08.820 --> 44:15.360
so check it out if you're so inclined. If we do go through the analysis, what we find is that the situation

409
44:15.360 --> 44:21.210
is not all that different
from the M equals two case, except that we get more precision.

410
44:21.210 --> 44:28.530
In particular, we can think
first about the probability to get the very best or one of
the two best approximations,

411
44:28.530 --> 44:31.740
which we can express like we have here.

412
44:31.740 --> 44:35.250
You can ignore this subscript of a one on the absolute value if you like.

413
44:35.250 --> 44:43.096
This is just a symbol that we
can use to remind ourselves that we're talking about
approximations on the circle where we think about theta equals zero

414
44:43.096 --> 44:51.210
and theta equals one as being the same. The point here is that
we're thinking about whatever choice of Y makes Y over two to the power M

415
44:51.210 --> 44:54.510
as close as possible to theta.

416
44:54.510 --> 45:03.270
And once again, just like we
had for the M equals two case, we're guaranteed to get this outcome Y with probability at least 40%.

417
45:03.270 --> 45:08.520
In fact, the probability is
at least four over pi squared, which is a little bit more than 40%.

418
45:08.520 --> 45:13.500
10 is not a bad
approximation to pi squared when you're in a hurry.

419
45:13.500 --> 45:21.330
And that's actually pretty remarkable. What we're talking about is getting the very best
approximation to theta as a fraction Y over two to the power M

420
45:21.330 --> 45:31.020
where Y is an integer. And we're getting the
very best approximation with probability greater than 40%.

421
45:31.020 --> 45:35.400
We can also think about
approximations that are worse.

422
45:35.400 --> 45:41.430
Specifically let's imagine
that Y isn't quite so good, and more specifically let's suppose

423
45:41.430 --> 45:48.270
that there's a better
approximation to theta of the same form that lies between theta and Y over two to the M,

424
45:48.270 --> 45:53.610
which can be expressed as
is written on the screen.

425
45:53.610 --> 46:00.780
In such a case the
probability to get this Y will be relatively small, at most 25%.

426
46:00.780 --> 46:09.840
It'll actually be lower than that, but 25% is what we get from
a pretty simple analysis, but it's good enough.

427
46:09.840 --> 46:15.240
As an example. Here's the plot we get when we use three control
qubits rather than two.

428
46:15.240 --> 46:22.756
This time I'm only
plotting the probabilities for the outcomes three, four, and five because I don't want the
figure to be too messy.

429
46:22.756 --> 46:28.140
When theta is equal to
one half for instance, we're guaranteed to get the outcome four.

430
46:28.140 --> 46:34.440
And so we take our
approximation to be four eighths or one half because two to
the power three is eight.

431
46:34.440 --> 46:42.060
And in this case we're exactly right. And as long as theta is closer to one half than it is to say three
eighths for instance,

432
46:42.060 --> 46:46.770
we get the outcome four with a probability higher
than the outcome three.

433
46:46.770 --> 46:51.930
And with probability,
again larger than 40%.

434
46:51.930 --> 47:01.320
Here's the plot when M is equal to four. And the curves actually
look pretty much identical, except that now we've zoomed
in by a factor of two.

435
47:01.320 --> 47:10.260
So now the outcomes that are plotted include seven, eight, and nine and we're taking the approximation to be one of these numbers
divided by 16 rather than eight.

436
47:10.260 --> 47:13.980
And I'll show one more plot where we increase to M equals five.

437
47:13.980 --> 47:18.510
And again we're gonna be
zooming in by a factor of two.

438
47:18.510 --> 47:26.700
And here it is. Once again the curves look
pretty much identical, but we're effectively
doubling our precision.

439
47:26.700 --> 47:34.560
And as before we obtained the very best approximation to theta, with probability greater than 40%.

440
47:34.560 --> 47:41.730
That's pretty amazing. But if 40% is not good enough
as a measure of confidence,

441
47:41.730 --> 47:51.120
what we can do is to run the procedure a small number of times, and
take the mode of the outcomes, meaning the one that
appears most frequently.

442
47:51.120 --> 47:58.590
And if we do that, we'll be extremely likely to end up with a very good approximation to theta.

443
47:58.590 --> 48:05.430
Remember by the way that every time we run the
phase estimation procedure we have that the eigenvector
comes out unchanged.

444
48:05.430 --> 48:11.040
So it is available for us to run the procedure
multiple times like this.

445
48:11.040 --> 48:19.380
In short, we're gathering
statistics about theta, and the point is that by doing this we can get a very precise
approximation to theta

446
48:19.380 --> 48:25.680
with very high confidence, and we don't need that many iterations of the procedure to do this.

447
48:25.680 --> 48:29.250
And that is how the phase
estimation procedure works.

448
48:29.250 --> 48:36.570
In the last part of the lesson, we'll apply the technique
of phase estimation to the integer factorization problem.

449
48:36.570 --> 48:44.670
As I mentioned at the start of the video, the way this works is that we consider an intermediate problem known as the order finding problem.

450
48:44.670 --> 48:51.690
We'll see how we can solve
the order finding problem using phase estimation, and then we'll briefly discuss how solving the order finding problem

451
48:51.690 --> 48:55.020
allows us to factor integers efficiently.

452
48:55.020 --> 49:00.840
The second part is completely classical and I'll only summarize the
basic idea in this video.

453
49:00.840 --> 49:05.670
But let's begin with the
order finding problem.

454
49:05.670 --> 49:10.140
First, let's get some
handy notation in place.

455
49:10.140 --> 49:17.310
For every positive integer N, we define ZN to be the integers
zero through N minus one.

456
49:17.310 --> 49:24.330
So for instance, Z one has a
single element which is zero, Z two has elements zero and one,

457
49:24.330 --> 49:28.440
z three has elements zero,
one and two, and so on.

458
49:28.440 --> 49:31.680
So ZN is a set.

459
49:31.680 --> 49:39.240
But we can also think about
it as more than a set. We can think about arithmetic operations like addition and multiplication on ZN

460
49:39.240 --> 49:43.290
by defining them modular N.

461
49:43.290 --> 49:47.340
For example, let's suppose
N is equal to seven.

462
49:47.340 --> 49:53.400
We have that three and five
are elements of Z seven and if we multiply them together we get 15

463
49:53.400 --> 49:57.570
which leaves a remainder of
one after dividing by seven.

464
49:57.570 --> 50:04.590
Sometimes we express this by writing that three times five is
congruent to one module seven, like is written here.

465
50:04.590 --> 50:08.250
But we can also simply write that three times five equals one.

466
50:08.250 --> 50:12.750
Of course three times five
isn't normally equal to one, it's equal to 15.

467
50:12.750 --> 50:18.990
But when it's clear that
we're working in Z seven meaning that multiplication
is defined modular seven,

468
50:18.990 --> 50:23.640
we can simply write that
three times five equals one.

469
50:23.640 --> 50:30.690
Now among the elements
of ZN for any positive N, some of them will have
GCD equal to one with N

470
50:30.690 --> 50:36.510
and some won't. And the elements that do have GCD equal to one with N are special.

471
50:36.510 --> 50:42.780
and we write ZN star to refer to the set of just these elements.

472
50:42.780 --> 50:47.559
So for example, here's Z 21 star.

473
50:47.559 --> 50:56.730
among the elements of Z 21, which there are 21 of course, it turns out that 12 of them have GcD equals of one
with 21 and the rest don't.

474
50:56.730 --> 51:03.930
In particular anytime that
we have an element of Z 21 that's divisible by either
three or seven, we skip it.

475
51:03.930 --> 51:11.100
There are various reasons
why this set is special, and one of the reasons is that anytime we have an element of ZN star

476
51:11.100 --> 51:17.370
and we consider the positive
integer powers of that number, we will always eventually
hit the number one,

477
51:17.370 --> 51:22.680
where just like before we're talking about multiplication modular N.

478
51:22.680 --> 51:28.500
the smallest positive integer power that gives us one is called
the order of that element.

479
51:28.500 --> 51:34.170
For example, think about the element A equals four in Z 21 star.

480
51:34.170 --> 51:41.070
four times four is 16, which is not equal to one modular of 21, but if we multiply by four one more time,

481
51:41.070 --> 51:46.320
we get 64, and 64 modular
21 is equal to one.

482
51:46.320 --> 51:51.300
So the order of four modular 21 is three.

483
51:51.300 --> 51:55.890
Getting to one like this always happens for all of the elements of ZN star.

484
51:55.890 --> 52:00.180
And by the way, it never
happens for elements of ZN that aren't in ZN star.

485
52:00.180 --> 52:06.930
So having GCD equal to
one with N like this is both necessary and
sufficient for this to happen.

486
52:06.930 --> 52:15.630
And just to finish up the
example of N equals 21, here are the smallest
positive integer powers for which this works for
each element of Z 21 star,

487
52:15.630 --> 52:21.835
and they can each be checked one by one.

488
52:21.835 --> 52:30.450
And now we can state the
order finding problem, which is simply to find the order for a given element in ZN star.

489
52:30.450 --> 52:36.690
To be precise, the input is
two positive integer A and N for which the GCD is equal to one,

490
52:36.690 --> 52:44.141
and the output is the
smallest positive integer R such that A to the power R is
congruent to one modular N,

491
52:44.141 --> 52:48.960
or equivalently the
smallest positive integer R for which A to the R is equal to one.

492
52:48.960 --> 52:53.370
Assuming we're doing arithmetic in ZN.

493
52:53.370 --> 53:00.960
This is believed to be a
computationally difficult problem, no efficient classical algorithm
is known for solving it.

494
53:00.960 --> 53:08.520
And as we'll discuss the problem is at least as hard as
integer factorization in the sense that if we have an algorithm for solving order finding,

495
53:08.520 --> 53:13.710
we would be able to use that algorithm to solve the integer
factorization problem efficiently.

496
53:13.710 --> 53:21.030
In fact, it goes the other way as well, meaning that if you happen to have an algorithm for factoring, you can use it to solve
the order finding problem.

497
53:21.030 --> 53:26.310
So the two problems are
in some sense equivalent in terms of their
computational difficulty.

498
53:26.310 --> 53:33.570
Now we'll see how we can solve
the order finding problem on a quantum computer
using phase estimation.

499
53:33.570 --> 53:41.970
To make a connection between the problems, let's imagine that we have a system whose classical state set is AN.

500
53:41.970 --> 53:49.530
For any choice of an element A in ZN star, we'll define an operation
MA like we have here.

501
53:49.530 --> 53:56.670
In words what MA does is to multiply by A, and here the multiplication is modular N.

502
53:56.670 --> 54:04.020
And for the remainder of this lesson, you should always think about
expressions inside of cats as being computed modular N,

503
54:04.020 --> 54:10.890
just so we can keep things simple and we don't have to keep on
writing mod N over and over.

504
54:10.890 --> 54:17.220
This is a unitary operation, but that's only true
because A is in ZN star.

505
54:17.220 --> 54:24.150
If the GCD of A and N isn't one, this operation won't be unitary.

506
54:24.150 --> 54:33.450
Here's an example. If N is equal to 15 and A is equal to two, which is in Z 15 star, then
this is the action of M two.

507
54:33.450 --> 54:41.670
And if you examine this
example for a few moments, you'll see that what's happening is that the elements of ZN are just getting permuted by this action.

508
54:41.670 --> 54:51.870
So it's both deterministic and unitary, which is to say that as a matrix, MA is a permutation matrix.

509
54:51.870 --> 54:58.230
And here's the main idea. The eigenvalues of MA are
very closely connected

510
54:58.230 --> 55:04.500
with the order of A. And by using phase estimation to approximate these
eigenvalues closely enough

511
55:04.500 --> 55:11.850
we can determine the order of A. So what exactly are the eigenvectors and the eigenvalues of MA?

512
55:11.850 --> 55:17.700
Well, we're not going to need all of them, we only need some of them.

513
55:17.700 --> 55:22.080
Let's start off with an easy example.

514
55:22.080 --> 55:28.930
Here's an eigenvector of MA, we've named it size zero, and it's given by the
sum of cat one, cat a,

515
55:28.930 --> 55:36.495
cat A squared, and so on up to cat A to the power R minus one, all divided by the square root of R

516
55:36.495 --> 55:40.320
to make it a unit vector. Here R is the order of A.

517
55:40.320 --> 55:44.490
And I'll reserve the
letter R for the order of A for the rest of the lesson.

518
55:44.490 --> 55:51.876
So whenever you see R, that's the order of A for
whatever A we're talking about.

519
55:51.876 --> 55:55.710
The eigenvalue associated
with this eigenvector is one.

520
55:55.710 --> 56:01.740
And we can verify that by
applying MA to this vector to see what we get.

521
56:01.740 --> 56:10.020
MA multiplies by A, so
we just need to increase each of the exponents by
one and this is what we get.

522
56:10.020 --> 56:14.700
But the order of A is R, so A to the power R equals one.

523
56:14.700 --> 56:18.930
And we can make that substitution.

524
56:18.930 --> 56:27.240
But that's the same vector
that we started with. All we've done is to
shuffle the cuts around but we're taking the sum so
this doesn't change anything.

525
56:27.240 --> 56:31.380
So MA times psi zero is equal to psi zero.

526
56:31.380 --> 56:35.400
So it's an eigenvector of
MA with eigenvalue one.

527
56:35.400 --> 56:43.080
That's a very simple
example of an eigenvector and to identify more of them, let's recall the same notation that we had earlier in the lesson.

528
56:43.080 --> 56:49.260
Omega R is the complex
number on the unit circle we get by taking E to the
power of two times pi times I

529
56:49.260 --> 56:57.720
divided by R. Last time we had an N rather than an R, but it still works the same
way for R in place of N.

530
56:57.720 --> 57:04.890
We need this number because
it's going to be appearing in the other eigenvectors
of MA that we'll identify.

531
57:04.890 --> 57:12.870
And now that we've recalled that notation, we can observe that this
vector named psi one is also an eigenvector of MA.

532
57:12.870 --> 57:19.500
It's similar to psi zero, we have exactly the same cats and we're summing them up and
dividing by the square of R.

533
57:19.500 --> 57:23.910
But this time we have various phases multiplying each of the cats.

534
57:23.910 --> 57:33.930
Omega R to the negative one for A, omega R to the negative two for A squared, and so on up to omega R to
the power negative R minus one

535
57:33.930 --> 57:45.570
for A to the power R minus one. So the power of omega R
is always negative one times whatever power of A
appears inside of the cat.

536
57:45.570 --> 57:52.650
I won't go through it in detail, but it is shown on the screen in case you'd like to re-watch the video and pause as needed.

537
57:52.650 --> 57:59.160
But if we do the multiplication and we simplify again using the fact that A to the power R is equal to one

538
57:59.160 --> 58:07.680
as well as the very important fact that omega to the power R is equal to one, what we'll find is that we
again have an eigenvector of MA.

539
58:07.680 --> 58:15.942
This time as we do the simplification, we'll need to pull out a factor of omega R to see that indeed we have an eogenvector

540
58:15.942 --> 58:22.650
and that vector of omega R represents the eigenvalue associated with this eigenvector.

541
58:22.650 --> 58:29.100
So that's a second eigenvector
eigenvalue pair of NA.

542
58:29.100 --> 58:37.170
We can identify additional eigenvectors using exactly the same reasoning, And in fact, if we simply replace omega R

543
58:37.170 --> 58:44.580
with omega R to the power J for each J between zero and R minus one, we'll always get an eigenvector,

544
58:44.580 --> 58:49.260
and the associated eigenvalue will be omega R to the power J.

545
58:49.260 --> 58:57.960
So this actually includes
psi zero and pis one, which we already saw
as well as R minus two, other eigenvector, eigenvalue pairs.

546
58:57.960 --> 59:04.680
They all work in basically the same way, and to verify them, we just need to know that A to the power R equals one

547
59:04.680 --> 59:09.180
as well as omega R to
the power R equals one.

548
59:09.180 --> 59:17.441
There are other eigenvectors of MA like cat zero for instance, but they aren't going to be useful to us and we don't need to worry about them.

549
59:17.441 --> 59:20.820
We only need to worry about psi zero through psi R minus one.

550
59:20.820 --> 59:26.820
Let's focus on psi one for a moment, just to try to understand why it is that we care about these eigenvectors

551
59:26.820 --> 59:33.960
and what they can tell
us about the order R, which is what we're trying to find.

552
59:33.960 --> 59:43.110
Supposing that we're given
the eigenvector psi one, we can attempt to learn
R in the following way.

553
59:43.110 --> 59:52.560
First, we perform phase
estimation on this eigenvector using a quantum circuit that
implements the operation MA.

554
59:52.560 --> 59:58.980
What we get is an approximation to theta, which is one over R in this case.

555
59:58.980 --> 60:06.600
And second because we're looking for R and we have an
approximation to one over R, the natural thing to do is
to compute the reciprocal

556
60:06.600 --> 60:13.350
and to round it off to
the nearest integer. We have to round like this
because R has to be an integer.

557
60:13.350 --> 60:18.360
But we don't have one of our R exactly, we just have an approximation to it.

558
60:18.360 --> 60:26.189
But if the approximation is good enough, we'll get R when we round,
which is what we're looking for.

559
60:26.189 --> 60:34.590
And now the question is how much precision do we need to correctly determine R by computing the reciprocal and rounding?

560
60:34.590 --> 60:42.330
Or in other words, how accurate does our
approximation need to be to make this all work?

561
60:42.330 --> 60:47.130
Well, it turns out that we do need a pretty accurate approximation.

562
60:47.130 --> 60:54.540
For example, we can't
afford to confuse one over R with one over R plus one, or one over R minus one for instance.

563
60:54.540 --> 61:01.980
In those two fractions, one over R plus one and
one over R minus one are pretty close to one
over R when R is large.

564
61:01.980 --> 61:10.710
But although we do need a
pretty accurate approximation, we don't need a ridiculously
accurate approximation, and it can be shown that
if our approximation

565
61:10.710 --> 61:18.570
satisfies the inequality that
we have here on the screen, then rounding off will
give us the right answer.

566
61:18.570 --> 61:27.510
I won't try to argue that in this video, but it is shown in the written
material for the lesson in case you're interested in the details.

567
61:27.510 --> 61:35.310
And if that's the accuracy
that we're going for, then it suffices to use a
number of control qubits in the phase estimation procedure

568
61:35.310 --> 61:38.970
that's equal to two times
the length of N plus one.

569
61:38.970 --> 61:46.230
Where as we had in the previous lessons, the length of N is the number of bits that we need to express N in binary.

570
61:46.230 --> 61:52.980
By the way, if we're content
to get the best approximation with probability at least 40% and we don't try to
increase our confidence

571
61:52.980 --> 61:56.790
like I described earlier, then we don't actually need the plus one.

572
61:56.790 --> 62:05.370
But in any case, we have that the number
of control qubits we need is linear in the length of N
written as a binary string.

573
62:05.370 --> 62:14.130
We've seen that if we have
the eigenvector psi one, we can use phase estimation to find R, provided we use enough accuracy.

574
62:14.130 --> 62:18.330
Unfortunately it's not so easy to get our hands on this eigenvector.

575
62:18.330 --> 62:22.020
So let's ask a different question.

576
62:22.020 --> 62:28.680
Suppose we don't have psi one, but rather we have psi
for a random choice of J.

577
62:28.680 --> 62:35.250
Can we still figure out what R is? Or at the very least can we
figure out something about R?

578
62:35.250 --> 62:42.150
And the answer is yes, we can figure out something
about R, at least on average.

579
62:42.150 --> 62:48.540
What we can do is to try
to figure out J over R using a very similar method
to the one that we just saw,

580
62:48.540 --> 62:51.780
but with a key difference.

581
62:51.780 --> 62:59.100
First, we'll do exactly the
same thing we did before, which is to run the phase
estimation procedure on the eigenvector psi J.

582
62:59.100 --> 63:06.600
And what we'll get is an
approximation to J over R, as opposed to one over R,
which is what we had before.

583
63:06.600 --> 63:13.950
But now we have a small problem, because computing the
reciprocal won't give us R, it will give us R over J.

584
63:13.950 --> 63:20.490
And by the way, we're not
assuming that we know what J is, we're simply given psi J for a random J,

585
63:20.490 --> 63:26.580
and we're not told what J is. So what can we do?

586
63:26.580 --> 63:34.380
Well, it turns out that there's a well-known
classical algorithm that can help us, called the
continued fraction algorithm.

587
63:34.380 --> 63:41.790
And what this algorithm can do is to take our approximation
Y over two to the M and tell us which fraction U over V,

588
63:41.790 --> 63:50.880
written in lowest terms, and where U and V are both
integers smaller than N is closest to our approximation.

589
63:50.880 --> 63:56.790
It's a truly fascinating algorithm, and if you're interested in it, you should definitely check it out.

590
63:56.790 --> 64:02.460
It's very closely connected to Euclid's algorithm for
computing GCDs in fact.

591
64:02.460 --> 64:06.570
But I won't say anything
more about it in this video.

592
64:06.570 --> 64:13.500
The point of this is that if we have a good
approximation to some fraction for which the numerator and
denominator aren't too big,

593
64:13.500 --> 64:17.880
the algorithm can recover the fraction, and that's what we're doing here.

594
64:17.880 --> 64:24.720
And now we're left with exactly
the same question as before, which is how much precision do we need?

595
64:24.720 --> 64:30.000
And it turns out that
exactly the same bound that we had before works in this case.

596
64:30.000 --> 64:37.440
And so choosing M in exactly
the same way as before works here as well.

597
64:37.440 --> 64:40.680
Now this isn't necessarily
going to tell us R.

598
64:40.680 --> 64:47.580
What we'll learn if we use
enough precision, is J over R, but that will be a
fraction in lowest terms.

599
64:47.580 --> 64:53.640
So we could get unlucky in the sense that this random choice of J could have common factors with R,

600
64:53.640 --> 65:01.020
and they'll be hidden from us. In the worst case for instance, we could get J equals zero and we will learn absolutely nothing.

601
65:01.020 --> 65:04.650
But that is literally the only
case where we learn nothing.

602
65:04.650 --> 65:11.550
In general, we'll at least
get a non-trivial factor of R, and if we're able to draw random samples

603
65:11.550 --> 65:18.750
and get psi J for different choices of J, we can in fact recover
R with high probability by computing the least common multiple

604
65:18.750 --> 65:25.320
of all of the denominators
that we observe. And this actually doesn't
require very many samples at all.

605
65:25.320 --> 65:31.740
The bottom line is that some choices of J will hide factors of R, but random choices of J

606
65:31.740 --> 65:35.460
won't be able to hide the
factors of R for long.

607
65:35.460 --> 65:45.240
So that is the idea. It remains to consider the implementation and in particular to figure
out how much it costs.

608
65:45.240 --> 65:52.560
The essence of the idea, to compute the order of a
given element A and ZN star is to apply the phase estimation procedure

609
65:52.560 --> 65:56.430
to the operation MA.

610
65:56.430 --> 66:03.840
Let's figure out what
the cost of doing this is as a function of the length of capital N, which I'll denote by little n.

611
66:03.840 --> 66:09.840
Here's a circuit for phase estimation. We're going to need little n qubits on the bottom part of the circuit

612
66:09.840 --> 66:17.190
to encode elements of ZN in binary. So we have N control qubits on top and little n qubits on the bottom,

613
66:17.190 --> 66:23.370
which is nice because that matches with the names that we
used earlier in the lesson.

614
66:23.370 --> 66:31.680
In order to count the
number of gates that we need for the entire circuit, let's focus first on the cost of the controlled unitary operations.

615
66:31.680 --> 66:39.780
If we use the techniques
from the previous lesson, lesson six, we can implement MA using big O of little n squared gates

616
66:39.780 --> 66:44.727
using efficient classical algorithms for arithmetic modular N.

617
66:44.727 --> 66:53.760
I'll skip the details in this video, but like several other
things I've talked about, you can read more about it in the written material for the lesson.

618
66:53.760 --> 66:57.000
It's not enough though
to implement just MA.

619
66:57.000 --> 67:03.330
We also need to implement MA squared, MA to the fourth power, to
the eighth power, and so on

620
67:03.330 --> 67:08.400
all the way up to MA to a power that's exponential in M.

621
67:08.400 --> 67:14.100
And we know we're going to need to take M to be linear in little n
to get enough precision.

622
67:14.100 --> 67:17.850
This is a big concern,
and I raised it earlier.

623
67:17.850 --> 67:28.080
If we were to implement powers
of MA by simply iterating MA, we'd be in trouble because all these iterations of MA
would incur exponential cost.

624
67:28.080 --> 67:33.270
Fortunately, we can play a trick to avoid this blow up in cost.

625
67:33.270 --> 67:38.490
What we can do is as follows, for each power K that we need.

626
67:38.490 --> 67:42.930
First, we compute A to
the power K, modular N.

627
67:42.930 --> 67:47.130
This is the modular exponentiation problem that I mentioned in lesson six.

628
67:47.130 --> 67:51.660
And it can be solved efficiently. And this is something that we can do with a classical computer.

629
67:51.660 --> 67:55.950
This computation doesn't
need to be performed by a quantum circuit at all.

630
67:55.950 --> 67:59.070
So let's let B be the result.

631
67:59.070 --> 68:03.060
So B is an element of ZN star.

632
68:03.060 --> 68:09.450
And second, in place of MA to the power K, we just use a circuit for MB.

633
68:09.450 --> 68:18.690
And that's it. B is just some element of ZN star, So the cost to implement MB
is big O of little n squared.

634
68:18.690 --> 68:25.770
In a nutshell, what we're doing is exponentating in ZN rather than exponentating
a quantum circuit.

635
68:25.770 --> 68:31.590
But the actual operation we
get is the same either way. It's just multiplication by A, K times.

636
68:31.590 --> 68:38.790
This is kind of a miracle in fact. And we wouldn't be able to
solve the order finding problem or effect integers efficiently
with a quantum computer

637
68:38.790 --> 68:42.450
if it wasn't for this.

638
68:42.450 --> 68:48.655
And now that we know that each of the controlled
unitary operations, including the powers, can be implemented

639
68:48.655 --> 68:53.520
at cost big O events squared, we can count the total
number of gates we need.

640
68:53.520 --> 69:01.260
We have N Hadamard gates, and because M is equal
to big O of little n, the cost is big O of little n.

641
69:01.260 --> 69:05.970
We have M controlled unitary operations that each have cost big O of N squared.

642
69:05.970 --> 69:09.480
So the total cost here
is big O of N cubed.

643
69:09.480 --> 69:14.710
And finally, the quantum Fourier transform has cost big O of n squared.

644
69:14.710 --> 69:17.850
So the total cost is big O of N cubed.

645
69:17.850 --> 69:25.320
In particular, we see that even with our
module exponentiation trick, the cost of the controlled
unitary operations dominates.

646
69:25.320 --> 69:30.300
But nevertheless, the cost
is polynomial in little n.

647
69:30.300 --> 69:37.440
There are also some classical
computations required, like computing the modular exponentiations and running the continued
fraction algorithm,

648
69:37.440 --> 69:47.700
but those computations
also have polynomial cost. And in fact, they can be done in big O of N cubed operations as well.

649
69:47.700 --> 69:54.780
There's only one remaining issue, and that is that we need to get our hands on one of these eigenvectors.

650
69:54.780 --> 69:58.350
How can we do this?

651
69:58.350 --> 70:03.530
The solution is actually very simple. We don't run the circuit
on an eigenvector.

652
70:03.530 --> 70:12.900
We just run it on the state one, meaning the binary
encoding of the number one, which we're thinking
about as an element of ZN.

653
70:12.900 --> 70:16.590
So let's make that
replacement in the diagram.

654
70:16.590 --> 70:20.670
The reason this works is because of this equation right here.

655
70:20.670 --> 70:27.210
The state cat one is in
fact a uniform superposition of the R eigenvectors that
we've been talking about.

656
70:27.210 --> 70:34.350
And that's not immediately obvious, but if you calculate the
sum, you should get cat one.

657
70:34.350 --> 70:41.250
And if we run the circuit on this state, the output that we'll get
will be exactly the same as if we'd randomly chosen J

658
70:41.250 --> 70:45.270
and run the procedure on
the eigenvector psi J.

659
70:45.270 --> 70:50.670
Again, that's not obvious, but an analysis reveals it to be true.

660
70:50.670 --> 70:56.070
And finally, that is it. We have an efficient quantum
algorithm for order finding.

661
70:56.070 --> 71:03.780
There's one very short part
of the lesson remaining and a concerns the relationship between integer factorization
and order finding.

662
71:03.780 --> 71:10.200
I mentioned that if we can solve the order finding problem efficiently, then we can also factor
integers efficiently.

663
71:10.200 --> 71:15.000
And I want to very briefly give you the main idea for how this works.

664
71:15.000 --> 71:21.360
It's completely classical. This part actually has nothing
to do with quantum computing.

665
71:21.360 --> 71:26.220
Here's a method for finding
a non-trivial factor of a given positive integer N.

666
71:26.220 --> 71:33.330
And by the way, this method only works when N is an odd number, and it's not a prime
number raised to a power.

667
71:33.330 --> 71:38.970
Those two cases when N
is even or a prime power can be handled separately.

668
71:38.970 --> 71:45.510
There are efficient classical methods for both detecting and
handling those two cases.

669
71:45.510 --> 71:52.320
This method is probabilistic. It might fail, but the
probability of failure will be at most a half,

670
71:52.320 --> 72:00.060
and we can simply run it
multiple times independently to reduce the probability
of error exponentially fast.

671
72:00.060 --> 72:07.290
First, we choose A between
two and N minus one at random, uniformly.

672
72:07.290 --> 72:10.290
Then we compute the GCD of A and N.

673
72:10.290 --> 72:15.390
And if the GCD happens
to be larger than one, then we've just been incredibly lucky.

674
72:15.390 --> 72:20.340
The GCD will be a factor of N and we can just output it and stop.

675
72:20.340 --> 72:27.900
Otherwise, the algorithm continues on and we now know that A is in ZN star.

676
72:27.900 --> 72:32.820
And now we compute the order of A, which is where we need a quantum computer.

677
72:32.820 --> 72:40.110
Or maybe we have a different
way to compute the order. The algorithm doesn't really
care where it comes from, but the only way that we know
how to do this efficiently

678
72:40.110 --> 72:44.250
is with a quantum computer.

679
72:44.250 --> 72:51.630
If the order of R is even, then we compute the GCD of
A to the power R over two minus one with N.

680
72:51.630 --> 72:59.010
And if that GCD is larger than one, then again we have a factor of N, so we output it and we stop.

681
72:59.010 --> 73:05.280
Otherwise the algorithm has failed. And in that case, we
can go back to the start and choose a different A

682
73:05.280 --> 73:08.880
and hope for a better
outcome the next time around.

683
73:08.880 --> 73:16.050
And that's it. And by the way, once
we found a factor of N, we can recurs on both that factor

684
73:16.050 --> 73:22.290
and divide it by that factor until we have a prime factorization of N.

685
73:22.290 --> 73:25.500
So why should this work?

686
73:25.500 --> 73:32.880
Well, there are two main points. The first is that because A to the power R is congruent to one modular N,

687
73:32.880 --> 73:37.080
we have that N divides A
to the power R minus one.

688
73:37.080 --> 73:44.610
Those two statements
are actually equivalent. This is the definition of mod N that you'll find in number theory books.

689
73:44.610 --> 73:49.590
Second, if R is even, then this equation that
we have here is true.

690
73:49.590 --> 73:53.640
This is the well-known formula
for a difference of squares.

691
73:53.640 --> 73:59.280
In fact, the equation is true for all R, but we need R over two to
be an integer in step four.

692
73:59.280 --> 74:07.740
And so if we put the two facts together, we see that every prime factor of N must divide one of the two
expressions in parentheses,

693
74:07.740 --> 74:12.690
because that's the only way
that N can divide the product.

694
74:12.690 --> 74:21.060
Now, it could be that every
single prime factor of N divides the first
expression in parentheses and not the second, but for our random A,

695
74:21.060 --> 74:27.900
that's not very likely. And so when we compute
the GCD in step four, we're likely to get the product

696
74:27.900 --> 74:32.760
of some of the prime
factors of N, but not all.

697
74:32.760 --> 74:37.710
To analyze this carefully
requires some number theory, but it is pretty basic number theory.

698
74:37.710 --> 74:43.560
So if you find number
theory to be interesting and you'd like to learn more about it, try working through this analysis.

699
74:43.560 --> 74:48.930
Working through things like this is an excellent way to learn more, but I will leave that to you.

700
74:48.930 --> 74:57.030
And that's the end of the lesson. In this lesson, we covered
the phase estimation problem, how we can solve it efficiently
on a quantum computer,

701
74:57.030 --> 75:04.200
and how we can apply the solution to obtain a polynomial
cost quantum algorithm for integer factorization.

702
75:04.200 --> 75:09.150
I hope you'll join me for the next lesson, which is on Grover's
quantum searching algorithm.

703
75:09.150 --> 75:10.100
Goodbye until then.
